<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<h3>What is the Model Context Protocol (MCP)?</h3>

<p>
  MCP is an open standard by Anthropic that provides a universal protocol for AI assistants to connect to external tools and data sources. It uses JSON-RPC 2.0 and defines three primitives: tools (actions the AI can perform), resources (data the AI can read), and prompts (reusable templates). Any MCP-compatible client (like Claude Desktop) can connect to any MCP server without custom integration code.
</p>

<h3>What programming languages can I use to build an MCP server?</h3>

<p>
  The official SDKs support TypeScript/JavaScript and Python. Community SDKs exist for Rust, Go, Java, C#, and other languages. TypeScript is the most mature option with the best documentation and examples. The protocol itself is language-agnostic — any language that can read/write JSON over stdio or HTTP can implement an MCP server.
</p>

<h3>How is MCP different from function calling or plugins?</h3>

<p>
  Function calling (like OpenAI's function calling) is model-specific and tightly coupled to one provider's API. MCP is a cross-platform protocol — build once, connect to any MCP client. Plugins (like ChatGPT plugins) required a specific manifest format and were limited to HTTP APIs. MCP supports stdio, SSE, and HTTP transports, works with local tools, and provides resources and prompts in addition to callable functions.
</p>

<h3>Is MCP secure? Can the AI do anything dangerous through MCP?</h3>

<p>
  MCP itself provides the protocol structure, but security is your responsibility as the server developer. Best practices include: only expose tools that are safe for the AI to call, validate all inputs with strict schemas, implement authentication for remote servers, use the principle of least privilege, and never expose destructive operations without confirmation mechanisms. The host application (like Claude Desktop) also prompts users before executing tool calls.
</p>

<h3>Can I connect multiple MCP servers to one AI client?</h3>

<p>
  Yes. Claude Desktop and other MCP clients support multiple concurrent server connections. Each server appears as a separate set of tools, resources, and prompts. This is one of MCP's key design strengths — you can compose capabilities from multiple specialized servers instead of building one monolithic server.
</p>

<h3>What is the difference between stdio and SSE transport?</h3>

<p>
  Stdio transport communicates via standard input/output streams — the client launches the server as a child process. It's simple, requires no network configuration, and is ideal for local development. SSE (Server-Sent Events) transport runs the server as an HTTP service — clients connect over the network. SSE is better for remote servers, shared servers, or when multiple clients need to connect simultaneously.
</p>

<h3>Do I need Claude Desktop to use MCP?</h3>

<p>
  No. Claude Desktop is one MCP client, but MCP is supported by many tools including Cursor, Windsurf, Cline, and various open-source clients. You can also build your own MCP client using the SDK. The protocol is open and not locked to any single application.
</p>

